name: Pinus taeda L.
occurrenceRemarks: The trees tend to grow in clusters, with a thick carpet of needles under them. They drop many spiky pinecones and have rough, plated bark that tends to attract lichen. The approximately 7-8 inch long needles are bright green and waxy-looking when alive, but brown when dead.

name: Pinus taeda L.
occurrenceRemarks: Found on the property itself. The ground here was sturdy and cool, with a richer earth texture than loam. Lots of grass rooted in this area, with many undergrowth kind of plants sheltering near the tree's base. Similar trees were found nearby and along the forested shore of the creek. The air was dry and cold. The tree grew in an open clearing, able to access total sunlight and weather nearly all day.

verbatimLocality: Livingston Lake State Park, Livingston, Texas
rights: © Roberto R. Calderón some rights reserved
name: Pinus taeda L.
occurrenceRemarks: Loblolly Pine (Pinus taeda) 21 February 2016 Lake Livingston State Park Livingston, Polk County, Texas Lake Livingston State Park is located in the East Texas Piney Woods and is in the region that comprises Loblolly Pine’s westernmost native range. It is also the most dominant pine tree in the state park. Loblolly Pine shares several common names including Arkansas Pine, North Carolina Pine, and Oldfield Pine. In the U.S. South it is the dominant commercial forest species, and “makes up over one-half of the standing pine volume. It is a medium-lived, intolerant to moderately tolerant tree with rapid juvenile growth. The species responds well to silvicultural treatments and can be managed as either even-aged or uneven-aged natural stands, or can be regenerated artificially and managed in plantations.” According to our cited source, “The native range of loblolly pine extends through 14 States from southern New Jersey south to central Florida and west to eastern Texas. It includes the Atlantic Plain, the Piedmont Plateau, and the southern extremities of the Cumberland Plateau, the Highland Rim, and the Valley and Ridge Provinces of the Appalachian Highlands. Loblolly pine does not grow naturally in the Mississippi River flood plain and is scarce in the deep, coarse sands of the lower Atlantic Plain and sandhills of North and South Carolina; it is important only in localized areas in southeastern Georgia and northern Florida.” Lake Livingston State Park is administered by the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department. Source: James B. Baker and O. Gordon Langdon, “Loblolly Pine,” range map, description, bibliography, United States Forest Service, US Department of Agriculture, accessed 2.28.16, http://www.na.fs.fed.us/pubs/silvics_manual/Volume_1/pinus/taeda.htm
